An '''estuarine turbidity maximum''', or ETM, is the zone of highest [[turbidity]] resulting from [[turbulence|turbulent]] [[sediment transport|resuspension of sediment]] and [[flocculation]] of [[suspended solids|particulate matter]] in an [[estuary]]. The turbulence is driven by tidal forces, waves, and [[density]]-drive currents that push a [[salt wedge]] upstream and beneath outflowing [[freshwater]] [[Discharge (hydrology)|discharge]].<ref>{{cite web|title=CRETM-LMER What is an ETM?|url=https://depts.washington.edu/cretmweb/whatis.html|website=depts.washington.edu|accessdate=3 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Schuttelaars |first1=H.M |last2=Friedrichs |first2=C.T. |year=2002 |title=Formation of Estuarine Turbidity Maxima in Partially Mixed Estuaries |url=http://www.vims.edu/~cfried/cv/2002/Schuttelaars_etal_2002_PECS.pdf |dead-url= |journal=Proceedings, Physics of Estuaries and Coastal Seas, 11th International Biennial Conference, 17–20 September |location=Hamburg, Germany |volume= |issue= |pages=180–183 |doi= |archive-url= |archive-date= |access-date=December 2, 2016 }}</ref>

