'''George Fryer Sternberg''' (1883–1969) was a paleontologist best known for his discovery in [[Gove County, Kansas|Gove County]], [[Kansas]] of the "fish-within-a-fish" of ''[[Xiphactinus audax]]'' with a recently eaten ''[[Gillicus arcuatus]]'' within its stomach. He was the son of [[Charles Hazelius Sternberg]] and nephew of [[Brigadier General (United States)|Brigadier General]] [[George M. Sternberg]] (1838–1915). The [[Sternberg Museum of Natural History]] at [[Fort Hays State University]] in [[Hays, Kansas]] is named for him and other members of his fossil collecting family like his father Charles Hazelius Sternberg (1850–1943), or his brother [[Charles Mortram Sternberg]] (1885–1981).
[[Image:Xiphactinus audax Sternberg Museum.jpg|thumb|left|250px|''[[Gillicus arcuatus]]'' within the stomach of ''[[Xiphactinus audax]]'', George F. Sternberg's most famous fossil find.]]

